Day 2 of hashtag#100DaysOfData 🎯

Early in my data journey, every query I wrote started with: SELECT *
It felt harmless. It felt easy. It wasn't.

Here's what SELECT * actually costs you 👇
1. Performance hit It fetches every column even if you need 4. On millions of rows — more I/O, more memory, slower query.
2. You pay for it (literally) In BigQuery, you're billed by data scanned. SELECT * on a large table = unnecessary cost. Every. Single. Time.
3. Breaks your pipeline Someone renames or removes a column upstream. Your dashboard breaks. Your report crashes. And you're debugging it on a Monday morning.
4. Indexes can't help you Databases use indexes to speed up queries. SELECT * bypasses them. You lose the performance boost entirely.
5. Exposes data you shouldn't Sensitive columns — salaries, internal IDs — get fetched without you realising.
6. Unreadable code Nobody knows what data you actually need. Makes collaboration and debugging a nightmare.

The fix?
Instead of: SELECT * FROM Customers;
Write: SELECT Id, FirstName, Email, Joined FROM Customers

Only pull what you need. Name what you use. Small habit. Massive difference at scale.
→ Never use SELECT * in production. Ever.

